Yes, or until the search space becomes empty.
class Solution {
    public int search(int[] nums, int target) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = nums.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {
            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            } else if (nums[mid] < target) {
                left = mid + 1;
            } else {
                right = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
}


//Brute force has a time complexity of **`O(n)`** because, in the worst case, it may need to check every element in the array before finding the target or determining that it doesn't exist. If the array contains `n` elements, the loop can run up to `n` times, and each iteration performs only one constant-time comparison (`nums[i] == target`), which is `O(1)`. Therefore, the total work is `n × O(1) = O(n)`. In contrast, binary search is `O(log n)` because it eliminates half of the remaining search space in every iteration instead of checking elements one by one.

